[17:59.96]	And cook to honest creatures: but 'tis not so;
[18:03.57]	'Twas but a bolt of nothing, shot at nothing,
[18:07.12]	Which the brain makes of fumes: our very eyes
[18:10.80]	Are sometimes like our judgments, blind. Good faith,
[18:14.85]	I tremble stiff with fear: but if there be
[18:18.32]	Yet left in heaven as small a drop of pity
[18:21.86]	As a wren's eye, fear'd gods, a part of it!
[18:25.26]	The dream's here still: even when I wake, it is
[18:29.02]	Without me, as within me; not imagined, felt.
[18:32.49]	A headless man! The garments of Posthumus!
[18:35.89]	I know the shape of's leg: this is his hand;
[18:39.43]	His foot Mercurial; his Martial thigh;
[18:42.54]	The brawns of Hercules: but his Jovial face
[18:46.08]	Murder in heaven?--How!--'Tis gone. Pisanio,
[18:49.26]	All curses madded Hecuba gave the Greeks,
[18:52.66]	And mine to boot, be darted on thee! Thou,
[18:55.98]	Conspired with that irregulous devil, Cloten,
[18:59.60]	Hast here cut off my lord. To write and read
[19:03.21]	Be henceforth treacherous! Damn'd Pisanio
[19:06.61]	Hath with his forged letters,--damn'd Pisanio--
[19:10.22]	From this most bravest vessel of the world
[19:13.76]	Struck the main-top! O Posthumus! alas,
[19:16.87]	Where is thy head? where's that? Ay me!
[19:19.98]	where's that?
[19:21.35]	Pisanio might have kill'd thee at the heart,
[19:24.97]	And left this head on. How should this be? Pisanio?
[19:28.94]	'Tis he and Cloten: malice and lucre in them
[19:32.49]	Have laid this woe here. O, 'tis pregnant, pregnant!
[19:36.39]	The drug he gave me, which he said was precious
[19:40.22]	And cordial to me, have I not found it
[19:43.40]	Murderous to the senses? That confirms it home:
[19:47.16]	This is Pisanio's deed, and Cloten's: O!
[19:50.34]	Give colour to my pale cheek with thy blood,
[19:53.96]	That we the horrider may seem to those
[19:57.21]	Which chance to find us: O, my lord, my lord!
[20:00.68]	[Falls on the body]
[20:01.55]	[Enter LUCIUS, a Captain and other Officers,
[20:01.98]	+ and a Soothsayer]
[20:02.41]Captain	To them the legions garrison'd in Gailia,
[20:05.81]	After your will, have cross'd the sea, attending
[20:09.64]	You here at Milford-Haven with your ships:
[20:13.11]	They are in readiness.
[20:15.14]CAIUS LUCIUS	But what from Rome?
[20:16.94]Captain	The senate hath stirr'd up the confiners
[20:20.34]	And gentlemen of Italy, most willing spirits,
[20:23.95]	That promise noble service: and they come
[20:27.35]	Under the conduct of bold Iachimo,
[20:30.24]	Syenna's brother.
[20:31.91]CAIUS	LUCIUS When expect you them?
[20:34.36]Captain	With the next benefit o' the wind.
[20:37.18]CAIUS LUCIUS	This forwardness
[20:38.85]	Makes our hopes fair. Command our present numbers
[20:42.82]	Be muster'd; bid the captains look to't. Now, sir,
[20:46.65]	What have you dream'd of late of this war's purpose?
[20:50.85]Soothsayer	Last night the very gods show'd me a vision--
[20:54.46]	I fast and pray'd for their intelligence--thus:
[20:58.22]	I saw Jove's bird, the Roman eagle, wing'd
[21:01.62]	From the spongy south to this part of the west,
[21:05.45]	There vanish'd in the sunbeams: which portends--
[21:09.21]	Unless my sins abuse my divination--
[21:12.17]	Success to the Roman host.
[21:14.48]CAIUS LUCIUS	Dream often so,
[21:16.00]	And never false. Soft, ho! what trunk is here
[21:19.54]	Without his top? The ruin speaks that sometime
[21:23.30]	It was a worthy building. How! a page!
[21:26.34]	Or dead, or sleeping on him? But dead rather;
[21:29.88]	For nature doth abhor to make his bed
[21:33.06]	With the defunct, or sleep upon the dead.
[21:36.39]	Let's see the boy's face.
[21:38.63]Captain	He's alive, my lord.
[21:40.43]CAIUS LUCIUS	He'll then instruct us of this body. Young one,
[21:44.19]	Inform us of thy fortunes, for it seems
[21:47.45]	They crave to be demanded. Who is this
[21:50.63]	Thou makest thy bloody pillow? Or who was he
[21:54.24]	That, otherwise than noble nature did,
[21:57.35]	Hath alter'd that good picture? What's thy interest
[22:01.47]	In this sad wreck? How came it? Who is it?
[22:04.79]	What art thou?
[22:06.24]IMOGEN	I am nothing: or if not,
[22:08.34]	Nothing to be were better. This was my master,
[22:12.02]	A very valiant Briton and a good,
[22:14.84]	That here by mountaineers lies slain. Alas!
[22:18.31]	There is no more such masters: I may wander
